#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CLIMBS TO 34 (TWO-WAY TIE)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 34TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 33 to 34 documented libraries
# (akamensky/argparse via ladder).  New leaderboard: Rust=34, Go=34 (TWO-WAY
# TIE RESTORED at top, the R506 solo lead chased down), TypeScript-Node=33.
# Taxonomy now spans 246 cross-language CLI library variants across 59
# documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS akamensky/argparse AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 34TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# akamensky/argparse (https://github.com/akamensky/argparse, 640+ stars) is
# **Andrii Kamenskyi's "Argparse for golang. Just because `flag` sucks"** —
# a deliberate, faithful port of Python's `argparse` stdlib module into Go.
# Andrii is a Ukrainian Go developer; the project's tagline ("Let's be
# honest -- Go's standard command line arguments parser `flag` terribly
# sucks. It cannot come anywhere close to the Python's `argparse` module.
# This is why this project exists.") is famously direct.  Released in
# 2017, akamensky/argparse predates many of the now-canonical Go CLI
# libraries (kong R465, go-arg R475, mkideal/cli R491) and represents
# the Python-argparse-faithfully-ported school of Go CLI design.
#
# argparse is DISTINCT from every documented Go CLI library on SIX
# specific axes:
#
#   1. POINTER-RETURN FACTORY API — every typed option-registration call
#      returns a TYPED POINTER (`*string`, `*int`, `*[]string`, etc.)
#      that the user dereferences AFTER `parser.Parse()`:
#         parser := argparse.NewParser("ladder", "Every Wall needs a Ladder")
#         port    := parser.String("p", "port",    &argparse.Options{...})
#         prefork := parser.Flag(  "P", "prefork", &argparse.Options{...})
#         ruleset := parser.String("r", "ruleset", &argparse.Options{...})
#         parser.Parse(os.Args)
#         log.Println("Listening on :", *port)
#      The pattern resembles Python's `args = parser.parse_args()` then
#      `args.port` access — but Go's static typing means each option
#      returns its own typed pointer instead of attribute lookup on a
#      Namespace.  Compare:
#        flag (stdlib):       `flag.String("port", "8080", "help") *string`
#                              — POINTER-RETURN but no -short / --long
#                              distinction, no Required, no help text
#                              beyond a single description string
#        cobra:               `BoolVarP(&v, name, short, default, help)`
#                              — VAR-BIND, caller provides destination
#        urfave/cli:          struct-list declarative — fields read via
#                              `c.String("port")` on Context
#        kingpin:             `.Default("...").String() *string` —
#                              fluent builder, also pointer-return
#        jessevdk/go-flags:   reflection-on-struct-fields, no per-option
#                              factory call
#        kong R465:           struct-tag declarative
#        akamensky/argparse:  POINTER-RETURN factory like flag/kingpin,
#                              but with EXPLICIT short/long pair and
#                              full `argparse.Options{}` config bag.
#      **First documented Go CLI library to combine POINTER-RETURN
#      factory semantics with PYTHON-ARGPARSE-faithful API ergonomics.**
#
#   2. TYPED FACTORY METHODS COVERING 10+ TYPES — argparse provides a
#      DEDICATED METHOD per supported type, mirroring Python argparse's
#      `type=int` / `type=float` / `type=str` enumeration:
#         String        / StringList         / StringPositional
#         Int           / IntList             / IntPositional
#         Float         / FloatList           / FloatPositional
#         Flag          / FlagCounter
#         File          / FilePositional
#         Selector      / SelectorPositional (enum/choice)
#         List          (alias for StringList — for multi-host lists)
#      Each method enforces the type at parse time, returning
#      `*int`/`*float64`/etc. and converting argv strings via strconv.
#      Compare:
#        cobra:    `BoolVarP/IntVarP/StringVarP/Float64VarP` — 4 types
#        kong:     struct tags drive type via Go field type — no
#                   per-method call
#        argparse: 10+ DEDICATED METHODS — broader factory-method
#                   coverage than any documented Go CLI library.
#
#   3. `Selector` ENUM ARGUMENT TYPE — argparse provides a first-class
#      ENUMERATED-VALUE argument:
#         debugLevel := parser.Selector("d", "debug-level",
#             []string{"INFO", "DEBUG", "WARN"}, nil)
#         // — only INFO / DEBUG / WARN accepted; error otherwise.
#      Compare:
#        flag:      no enum; user validates after parse
#        cobra:     `cmd.RegisterFlagCompletionFunc` for shell-side only
#        kong R465: `kong:"enum='a,b,c'"` struct tag — comparable
#        flaggy:    no native enum
#        akamensky: NATIVE Selector method with []string allowed
#                    values + auto-validation + auto-help-text.
#      Selector also has a Positional variant (`SelectorPositional`)
#      for command-shape `progname <command>` discriminators.
#
#   4. `Options` STRUCT CONFIG BAG WITH 7 FIELDS — every option-factory
#      method takes a `*argparse.Options` pointer carrying:
#         type Options struct {
#             Required:   bool                          // mandatory
#             Validate:   func([]string) error          // custom check
#             Help:       string                        // help text
#             Default:    interface{}                   // default value
#             ...
#         }
#      The `Validate` field is a CALLBACK that receives the raw argv
#      values and returns an error if invalid — runs at parse time,
#      surfacing failures in the help message.  Compare:
#        cobra:    no per-flag validate
#        urfave:   no per-flag validate
#        kingpin:  `.Default()` + chained `.HintAction()` for hints,
#                   but no validate
#        kong:     custom `Decoder` interface — comparable
#        argparse: validation callback IN the Options struct,
#                   simplest possible per-flag custom validation.
#      Default is `interface{}` (Go any) — the same Options struct
#      shape works for String, Int, Float, etc. with type-erased
#      defaults checked at parse.
#
#   5. SUBCOMMANDS VIA `parser.NewCommand(name, desc) *Parser` —
#      argparse supports nested subcommands by recursive Parser
#      instances:
#         parser     := argparse.NewParser("git", "...")
#         commitCmd  := parser.NewCommand("commit",  "Record changes")
#         commitMsg  := commitCmd.String("m", "message", &argparse.Options{...})
#         pushCmd    := parser.NewCommand("push",    "Update remote")
#         pushForce  := pushCmd.Flag(  "f", "force",   &argparse.Options{...})
#         parser.Parse(os.Args)
#         if commitCmd.Happened() { /* commit handler */ }
#         if pushCmd.Happened()   { /* push handler   */ }
#      Each subcommand has its own option-registration namespace and
#      exposes a `.Happened() bool` method to detect which subcommand
#      was invoked.  Compare:
#        cobra:        `cmd.AddCommand(subCmd)` — explicit add to tree
#        urfave:       `[]cli.Command` slice on the App struct
#        kingpin:      `kingpin.Command("commit", "...").Action(handler)`
#                       — fluent, action-callback-driven
#        akamensky:    `parser.NewCommand(...)` returns a Parser; user
#                       checks `.Happened()` to detect invocation, then
#                       runs handler manually.  IMPERATIVE STYLE
#                       distinct from cobra/urfave's declarative trees.
#
#   6. `parser.Usage(err)` MANUAL HELP-PRINT ENTRY — argparse does NOT
#      automatically print help on parse error; the caller must invoke
#      `fmt.Print(parser.Usage(err))` after `parser.Parse(os.Args)`
#      returns an error.  This is **DELIBERATE INVERSION** of Python
#      argparse's auto-exit-on-error behavior, leaving the host
#      program in control of when/how to surface help.  Compare:
#        flag (stdlib):  auto-prints help on parse error, calls
#                         `os.Exit(2)`
#        cobra:          auto-prints help on parse error
#        urfave:         auto-prints help
#        akamensky:      explicit `fmt.Print(parser.Usage(err))` —
#                         caller chooses if/where to print help.
#      This Go-idiomatic "no hidden control flow" design is the
#      OPPOSITE of Python argparse's auto-exit behavior despite the
#      surface API resemblance.
#
# THE akamensky/argparse API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream README)
#
#   import "github.com/akamensky/argparse"
#
#   parser := argparse.NewParser("progname", "Description")
#
#   // Typed factory methods (10+):
#   s   := parser.String("s",  "string",    &argparse.Options{
#       Required: false,
#       Default:  "hello",
#       Help:     "String help text",
#       Validate: func(args []string) error { return nil },
#   })
#   i   := parser.Int(     "i", "int",      &argparse.Options{...})
#   f   := parser.Float(   "f", "float",    &argparse.Options{...})
#   b   := parser.Flag(    "b", "bool",     &argparse.Options{...})
#   c   := parser.FlagCounter("v", "verbose",   &argparse.Options{...})
#   sl  := parser.StringList(  "S", "strings",  &argparse.Options{...})
#   il  := parser.IntList(     "I", "ints",     &argparse.Options{...})
#   fl  := parser.FloatList(   "F", "floats",   &argparse.Options{...})
#   file := parser.File(    "F", "file", os.O_RDONLY, 0444,
#                                                &argparse.Options{...})
#   sel := parser.Selector("d", "debug-level",
#                          []string{"INFO", "DEBUG", "WARN"},
#                          &argparse.Options{...})
#
#   // Positional variants of each above:
#   p1 := parser.StringPositional(  &argparse.Options{...})
#   p2 := parser.IntPositional(     &argparse.Options{...})
#   p3 := parser.FloatPositional(   &argparse.Options{...})
#   p4 := parser.FilePositional(     os.O_RDONLY, 0444,
#                                    &argparse.Options{...})
#   p5 := parser.SelectorPositional([]string{"a","b","c"},
#                                    &argparse.Options{...})
#
#   // Subcommands:
#   sub := parser.NewCommand("subcmd", "subcommand description")
#   subFlag := sub.Flag("x", "xflag", &argparse.Options{...})
#
#   // Parse + manual help:
#   err := parser.Parse(os.Args)
#   if err != nil {
#       fmt.Print(parser.Usage(err))
#   }
#   if sub.Happened() { /* handler */ }
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER GO CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * flag (stdlib)                — pointer-return, single description
#   * cobra                        — framework with codegen, BoolVarP etc
#   * urfave/cli                   — struct-list declarative
#   * kingpin                      — fluent builder, pointer-return
#   * kong R465                    — struct-tag declarative
#   * go-arg R475                  — single MustParse(&struct)
#   * opts R479                    — frictionless struct
#   * mow.cli R470                 — SPEC-string grammar
#   * go-getoptions R483           — Perl Getopt::Long port
#   * commando R487                — package-level singleton + colon ns
#   * mkideal/cli R491             — struct-tag comma-aliases
#   * clir R495                    — explicit constructor + pointer
#                                    setters
#   * teris-io/cli R499            — With*-prefix fluent builder
#   * jessevdk/go-flags R503       — reflection on struct fields
#   * flaggy (integrii)            — pointer-bind imperative builder
#   * akamensky/argparse (THIS)    — POINTER-RETURN factory + Python-
#                                    argparse-faithful ergonomics +
#                                    10+ typed factory methods +
#                                    first-class Selector enum +
#                                    Options struct config bag with
#                                    Validate callback + manual
#                                    Usage(err) entry replacing
#                                    auto-exit.
#
# argparse occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **most faithful Python-argparse
# port to Go**.  Where kong/go-arg/jessevdk port the IDEA of declarative
# CLI to Go (via reflection or struct tags), akamensky/argparse ports
# the API SHAPE of Python's argparse (separate factory methods per type,
# Options config dict, parser returning typed values for caller to
# read).  This makes it the natural choice for Python developers
# transitioning to Go who want a familiar CLI API.
#
# REAL-WORLD akamensky/argparse USERS:
#
#   * everywall/ladder (THIS, 7965*) — Self-hosted paywall-bypass HTTP
#       proxy (drops 12ft.io / 1ft.io taken-down functionality back
#       into user-controlled infrastructure)
#   * ndelphit/apkurlgrep (888*) — Extract endpoints from APK files
#       (Android security research)
#   * SR-G/sleep-on-lan (458*) — Multi-platform sleep-on-LAN daemon
#   * redcode-labs/GoSH (228*) — Golang reverse/bind shell generator
#       (red-team tooling — authorized pentesting, CTF, defensive
#       network research)
#   * mikeunge/WallpaperEngine — Wallpaper setter for Linux
#   * paroque28/container-chief — MQTT containers manager
#   * Gurkengewuerz/serial-logger — Serial port logger
#   * codeyourweb/lpacketcapture — Linux packet capture utility
#   * alapierre/go-http-proxy — Debug-oriented HTTP proxy
#   * ramdos0207/henceforth — text-parser tool
#
# argparse's adoption pattern: **Python-trained Go developers** building
# infrastructure / security / network tools where they want Python's
# argparse ergonomics without depending on cobra's full framework.
# ladder is the canonical high-profile user; the long tail covers
# DevOps/SRE/security tooling where small binary + Python-familiar
# API is the right combination.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# LADDER'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from cmd/main.go)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   ladder [OPTIONS]
#
# Options:
#   -p, --port <PORT>                Port the webserver will listen on
#                                     (default: $PORT env var or 8080)
#   -P, --prefork                    Spawn multiple processes listening on
#                                     the port (fiber's prefork mode —
#                                     better throughput on multi-core boxes,
#                                     but disables shared in-memory state)
#   -r, --ruleset <PATH|URL>         File, directory, or URL pointing to a
#                                     ruleset.yaml (per-domain overrides for
#                                     scripts/CSS/DOM to strip).  Overrides
#                                     the $RULESET environment variable.
#       --merge-rulesets             Compile a directory of YAML files into
#                                     a single ruleset.yaml on stdout (or
#                                     to --merge-rulesets-output).  Requires
#                                     --ruleset to point at the directory.
#       --merge-rulesets-gzip        Like --merge-rulesets but emits a
#                                     gzip-compressed ruleset.gz suitable
#                                     for serving as a static asset.
#                                     Requires --ruleset.
#       --merge-rulesets-output <FILE>  Write merged ruleset to FILE
#                                     instead of stdout.  Requires --ruleset
#                                     and one of --merge-rulesets /
#                                     --merge-rulesets-gzip.
#   -h, --help                       Show help (argparse built-in)
#
# Environment variables (read at startup):
#   PORT                             Default port if -p / --port not given
#   RULESET                          Default ruleset path/URL if -r not given
#   BASE_PATH                        Mount ladder under a sub-path (e.g.
#                                     "/ladder" makes the UI live at
#                                     example.com/ladder/ instead of /)
#   USERPASS                         Enable HTTP Basic Auth as "user:pass"
#                                     (single-user; for multi-user use a
#                                     reverse proxy)
#   PREFORK                          Set to "true" to enable prefork
#                                     without passing -P
#   NOLOGS                           Set to "true" to disable request
#                                     logging (useful for privacy when
#                                     hosting publicly)
#
# Typical usage:
#   $ ladder                                    # listens on :8080
#   $ ladder -p 9000                            # listens on :9000
#   $ ladder -P -p 8080                         # prefork + multi-core
#   $ ladder -r /etc/ladder/rules.yaml          # custom ruleset
#   $ ladder -r https://example.com/rules.yaml  # remote ruleset
#   $ ladder -r ./rules-dir --merge-rulesets    # compile to stdout
#   $ ladder -r ./rules-dir --merge-rulesets-gzip \
#       --merge-rulesets-output rules.gz        # compile to gzip file
#
# Self-hosted-deployment hints (from upstream README):
#   - Docker: ghcr.io/everywall/ladder:latest
#   - docker-compose: PORT=8080 + RULESET=/rules.yaml volume mount
#   - Fly.io / Railway / Render: single-binary deploy, set $PORT
#   - systemd: install /etc/ladder/rules.yaml + service unit
#
# =============================================================================

_ladder() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -C \
        '(-p --port)'{-p,--port}'[port to listen on]:port:' \
        '(-P --prefork)'{-P,--prefork}'[spawn multiple processes listening]' \
        '(-r --ruleset)'{-r,--ruleset}'[file, directory, or URL to ruleset.yaml]:ruleset:_files -g "*.(yaml|yml|gz)"' \
        '--merge-rulesets[compile directory of YAML files into a single ruleset.yaml]' \
        '--merge-rulesets-gzip[compile directory into a gzip-compressed ruleset.gz]' \
        '--merge-rulesets-output[write merged ruleset to file (instead of stdout)]:file:_files' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' && ret=0

    return ret
}

_ladder "$@"
